eng: The touture of the grave is only known by the corpse
A reserve will not decay
He who praises rain has been rained on.
Great wit drives away wisdom
He who does not admit defeat is not a sportsman
He wanders around by day a lot, learns a lot
If you are absent you lose your share
Shark is the famous one in sea the but they many others
kisw: Avumaye baharini papa kumbe wengi wapo.

eng: After hardship comes relief.
An evil Indian but his bussiness is good.
A flag follows the direction of the wind.
The evil spirit of a man is a man.
The drunkard's money is being consumed by palm-wine trapper.
A handsome finger gets the ring.
A sinking vessel needs no navigation.
Constant dipping will empty goud of honey
kisw: Chovya - chovya yamaliza buyu la asali.

eng: Clouds are the sign of rain
Blood is thicker than water
the remedy of fire is fire
the curse of the fowl does not bother the kite.
Gratitude of a donkey is a kick.
A wepon which you don't have in hand wont kill a snake.
Follow bees and you will get honey
Put a riddle to a fool a clever person will solve it
The skin of yesteday's sugarcane is a havest to an ant.
kisw: Ganda la mua la jana chungu kaona kivuno.

eng: Little by little fills up the measure.
They is no distance that has no end.
They is no secret between two people.
Hurry hurry has no blessings
Anger brings loss(Damage)
It is better to lose your eyes than to lose your heart.
kisw: Heri kufa macho kuliko kufa moyo

eng: Better to stumble with toe than toungue.
Voluntary is better than force
He laughs at scar who has received no wound.
kisw: Hucheka kovu asiye kuwa na jeraha.

eng: Kindness does not go rotten.
If you don't know death look at the grave.
A good name shines in the dark.
An ivory tooth is not cure for the lost tooth.
kisw: Jino la pembe si dawa ya pengo.

eng: Effort will not counter faith.
The village cock does not crow in town.
An infidel who does you good turn is not like a Muslim who does not
A rope parts where it is thinnest.
A guine- fowl not lay eggs on strange places
Usage is like law
Better delay and get there.
A bad job is not as wothless as a good game
The creaking of the door deprives me of no sleep.
Nine is near ten.
Arrogance is not gentlemanly.
Everyone should contribute when collection is made.
One finger canot kill a louse.
That is fashionable in town is never prohibited.
That which eats you up is in your clothing.
Every vessel has its own waves
Every door with its own key
To every child his own neck ornament
Every who streches a skin on a drum,pulls the skin own his own side.
Every bird flies with its own wings.
kisw: Kila ndege huruka na mbawa zake

eng: The beareved begins the wailing latter others join.
kisw: Kilio huanza mfiwa ndipo wa mbali wakaingia.

eng: Along silence followed by mighty noise.
One fire brand after another keeps fire burning.
kisw: Kinga na kinga ndipo moto uwakapo.

eng: A barber does not shave himself.
Mouth is the home of words.
What the heart desires is medicine to it.
A new thing is a souce of joy even if is sore.
Refusing and wanting at the same time.
what is not eaten by a man,let the devil eat it.
You canot know the bugs of a bed that you have not lain on.
kisw: Kitanda usicho kilala hujui kunguni wake.

eng: Shadow of a stick canot protect one from the sun.
kisw: Kivuli cha fimbo hakimfichi mtu jua

eng: The blindnes of that one is his good fortune
kisw: Kiwi cha yule ni chema cha;hata ulimwengu uwishe.

eng: A good thing sells it self a bad one advertises it self
A handfull of water can not be grasped.
One fault does not warrant divorce of a wife
A goshawk is an egg child,if sleeps hungry its his own fault.
ie One eye of a master sees more than four of a servent.
Giving advice but no one listens.
The fear of God is not wearing a white turban.
Leave well alone! You wont improve matters by going on tinkering
Death has its advantages too ie it benifits those who inherit.
The death of not a relative is a wedding.Compared to a death of a relative
When the head of the family dies,that family breaks up.
To live long is to see much.
To stumble is not falling down but it is to go forward.
kisw: Kujikwa si kuanguka,bali ni kwenda mbele

eng: Borrowing is like a wedding ,repaying is like mourning.
A hen does not break her own eggs.
A new fowl always has string around its legs.
Eating is sweet ,digging is weariness.
It is not hard to nurse a pregnency,but it is hard to bring up a child.
kisw: Kulea mimba si kazi kazi kulea mwana

eng: Where they is mourning someone has died.
The timid crow withdraws his wings from harm.
You may climb a thorn tree,and be unable to come down.
To get lost is to learn the way.
Charity is the matter of the heart not of the pocket.
kisw: Kutoa ni moyo usambe ni utajiri.

eng: Old rust is for the stranger.
Cooling the tongs is not end of forging.
kisw: Kuzima koleo si mwisho wa uhunzi.

eng: i.e.timidity often ends in a laugh, bravado in a lament.
kisw: Kwa mwoga huenda kicheko na kwa shujaa huenda kilio.

eng: To run is not neccessarily to arrive.
Where there trees,there are no builders.
A vessel running agroud has no captain.
They is no incence for something rotting.
One's foul smelling does not sicken one self but merely disguts one.
Today is today who says tommorrow is a liar
kisw: Leo ni leo asemayo kesho ni mwongo.

eng: That which is written by God is what is.
Good and evil will never mix.
Things dont just happen by accidents
What is benig talked about is here,and if its not it's comming around behind.
Out of sight out of mind.
You dont take viengeance on silliness.
Eyes have no screens,they see all that is within view.
Two bulls do not live in the same shade.
A dead person is not asked for a shroud.
water follows current.i.e.swim with current.
Water flows down the valley does not climb the hill.
If you take of your clothes for water you must bathe.
kisw: Maji ukiyavuliya nguo huna budi kuyaogelea.

eng: You can not know the extent of water in a pond that you have never been to.
Water in a coconut shell is like an ocean to an ant.
kisw: Maji ya kifufu ni bahari ya chungu.

eng: When tide is high,it ebbs.
He who climbs a ladder comes down again.i.e.What goes up must come down
If water is split,it can not be gathered up.
Big houses conceal a lot.
Regrets are like a child,They come some considerable time after event.
With many captains,the ship does not sail properly.i.e.Too many cooks spoil the broth.
Words alone wont break bones.
Pleasent words will draw the snake from its hole.
When a poor man gets something he boasts of his new wealth.
A poor man does not pick up things if does they say he stole them.
A por man with his child a rich man with his wealth.
kisw: Masikini na mwanawe tajiri na mali yake.

eng: Why drive away fowls from the dung you do not eat yourself?
Old droppings do not stink.
A double jointed arm follows the leg action.i.e Like father like son.
Running on the roof finishes at the edge.
When an oxhorn of a news man is sounded,something is wrong.
kisw: Mbiu za mgambo ikilia kuna jambo.

eng: One who selects his hoe is not real farmer.
He who selects coconut with great care ends up getting a bad cocon
You dont throw stones at an approching craclin noise in the bush wait and see what is it first
A traveller does not make a mess where he had made a camp as he might one day come back.
He who fears the crying of a child,will cry himself.
Rice is all one but they are many ways of cooking it
He who laughs at a cripple will not die without becoming himself
A dancer will not become crippled for dancing calls for grace.
He who dances at home will be rewarded.
He who plays with mud will get splashed.
He who ridicules the good will be overtaken by evil.
He who digs a pit will fall into it himself.
The maker of wooden spoons saves his hand from fire.
He who dips his finger into honey does not dip it once.
He who earns calamity,eats it with his family.
He who earns his living in the sun,eats in the shade.
He who riducules a deformed person becomes deformed himself.
The teeth of a dog do not lock together.i.e brothers do not harm one another when they fight.
A drowning man catches at the water.
One who hides private parts wont get a child.
A potter eats from a potsherd.
One follows bees will never fail to get honey.
He who is expled from home has no where to go
A lazy person with a nephwe does not eat dry rice.
kisw: Mgaagaa na upwa hali wali mkavu.

eng: A witchdoctor does not cure himself.
If the palmwine tapper is praised,he dilutes the palm-wine with water
A stranger is like a white fowl (noticeble)
Let the guest come so that the host may benifit.
A sick person is not asked for porridje.
I am a mud hut, I can not stand shocks.
When a fool becomes enlightened,the wise man is in trouble.
A messenger is not killed
The one who is caught with the skin is the thief.
He who fixes his mind much on water ends up not drinkink it
A poor man has no contempt.
A wife is like clothes and banana plant needs weeding.
A single hand can not slaughter a cow.
A single hand can not nurse a child.
An empty hand is not licked.
Kiss the hand you can not cut.
One who has little relish must eat sparingly.
Its nice throw a spear to a pig,but painful when thrown to you.
kisw: Mkuki kwa nguruwe mtamu,kwa mwanadamu uchungu.

eng: The farmer is one but those who eat fruits of his labour are many.
kisw: Mkulima ni mmoja walaji ni wengi.

eng: He who eats another mans food will have his own food eaten by others.
kisw: Mla cha mwenziwe na chake huliwa.

eng: He who eats bitter things gets sweet things too.
kisw: Mla cha uchungu na tamu hakosi.

eng: He who devours his neighbour's fowl,its foot prints will give him away.
kisw: Mla kuku wa mwenziwe miguu humwelekeya.

eng: The eater of a goat pays back a cow.
The real eater is todays eater not yesterdays.
kisw: Mla mla leo mla jana kala nini?

eng: He who eats with you will not die with you except he who was born with you.
kisw: Mla nawe hafi nawe ila mzaliwa nawe.

eng: He who who flings a stone amid a crowd,does not know the it hits.
He who enjoys the first fruit of a country is son of that country.
One who keeps silent,endures.
He who drinks water with one hand finds out his thirst is still there.
kisw: mnywa maji kwa mkono moja,Kiu yake i pale pale.

eng: Take one,not that you may return with ten.
Fire does not beget fire in the end it begets ashes.
One who rides two horses at once will split asunder.
He who sows disorderly fashion will eat likewise.
If a native of pemba can get a log he does not relive himself on the ground.ie nothing but the best
Pemba does not run away fro a small shower.
kisw: Mpemba hakimbii mvua ndogo.A native o.

eng: He who fights with a wall will only hurt his hand.
He who becomes blind in his old age does not lose his way.
A traveller is poor,even though he being a ruler.
A hunter is not afraid of thorns.
One who talks to himself can not be wrong.Ie no one to correct him.
If an arrow goes into a forest it is not lost.
A tailor does not select his cloth.
Do not abuse palm-wine tappers while drunkness persists.
Do not abuse midwives while child-bearing continues.
A patient man will eat ripe fruits.
He who requires what is under the bed must bend for it.
He who boasts of his ancestry unduly will bring plenty of trouble upon himself.
kisw: Mtaka nyingi nasaba hupata mwingi msiba.

eng: He who desires to make something does not announce his intentions ,just turns them into actions.
He who desires all,misses all
He who likes to eat cows hump will not fail to grow fat.
An aimless wanderer wears away his legs.
A connoisseur never comes to the end of desire.
A log can not move save by the help of rollers.
An old man always keeps something in reserve.
When a child cries for a razor give it him.i.e. Let him learn by experience.
As you bring up a child ,so he will be.
The child of a snake is a snake.
A person does not objects to being called, he objects to what he is called for.
A person scratches himself where his hand can reach.
A person is asked about his dress not what he has eaten.
One who always depends on his brother will die poor.
The carrier of a secret message is not told its meaning.
Serve even an unbeliever to attain your own ends.
If you throw a millipede you should throw away the stick you picked it up with.
kisw: Mtupa jongoo hutupa na mti wake.

eng: A husband of a mother is a father
God does not concell a(hypocrite) liar.
One who stores half grown fruit eats it rotten.
The space under the bed is like a mat.
The destroyer of a country is a citizen of that country
A fisheman knows where to look for an octopus.
He who renounces his ancestrey is like a slave.
He who spekes ill of someone close to you in your presence sends you to tell him so.
He who trusts in God lacks nothing.
An obstinete child does not suffer save on the day of festival.
kisw: Mwana mkaidi hafaidi mpaka siku ya idi.

eng: To a seamen of Kwale,death by water is common experience.
kisw: Mwana maji wa kwale kufa maji mazowea.

eng: The child who grows up with you is your fellow.
kisw: Mwana mkuwa nawe ni mwenzio kama wewe.

eng: A chick is not taught how to scratch up the ground.
The child of lion is a lion.
Give a wizard a child to bring up.
He who is after two things at the same time,one will surely escape him
The begining is bud the end is coconut.
The begining of a mat-making is two slips of raffia leaf.
kisw: Mwanzo wa chanzo ni chane mbili.

eng: The begining of a dance is" lele" i.e.just one man singing hu lalaaaa.
One who curses someone in public,brings it on himself in private.
kisw: Mwapiza la nje hupata la ndani.

eng: He who nurses vegeance is not called wise.
One who walks with no reason is not like one who sits without reason,the one who walks might pick up something.
kisw: Mwenda bure si mkaa bure,huenda akaokota.

eng: A person who is in too much of a hurry stubs his toe.
He who goes to the quarterdeck and forecastle will return to the hold eventualy.
kisw: Mwenda tezi na omo marejeo ngamani

eng: A noisy person is harmless.
One with a scar,do not think him healed.
He who is carried on the back must cling on.
He who slaughters a beast does not hesitate about skinning it
One who has been bitten by a snake,when he sees grass he he gets afraid.i.e.Once bitten twice shy.
kisw: Mwenye kuumwa na nyoka akiona jani hushtuka.

eng: One who has eyes is not told to look(he does it himself)
Let a strong man pass
A hungry man observes no taboos.
A hasty person misses the sweet things (because he cannot wait for the fruit to ripen).
A satisfied person does not know the hungry man. Or: He that is warm thinks that all are so.
He who has an axe does not lack firewood.

She who is pregnant, is pregnant-even though she wrap herself in an 'mkaja' (i.e you don't achieve something by merely pretending you have achieved it.) (Mkaja is the cloth a woman wears round her stomach after giving birth).
kisw: Mwenye tumbo ni tumbole, angafunga mkaja.

eng: When your Companion is being shaved, put water (on your head). ('Be prepared-eg. when you see a neighbouring country being invaded prepare to face the same situation yourself) Or: When your neighbour's house is on fire, take care of your own.
A thief is a rogue but the one who repays is a gentleman
kisw: Mwibaji na watwana, mlifi ni mwungwana.

eng: Your companion's body is beside (i.e. not a part of) your body.
kisw: Mwili wa mwenzio ni kando ya mwilio.

eng: A thief is caught by his fellow thief. Or: Set a thief to catch a thief.
He who asks for salt does so for his own cooking pot
The washer of corpses does no harm to the dead.
The corpse-washer is washed (in his turn). Or: Tit for tat.
The washer conceals the corpse (i.e gives nothing away).
Joke, joke, discharges pus (i.e. do not dismiss even a small scratch as if it were only a joke-it may go bad) Or: A stitch in time saves nine.
One who gives birth cannot avoid (ritual) defilement
Your companion's burden is (no more than) a load of kapok (to you). Or: The burden is light on the shoulder of another.
kisw: Mzigo Wa mwenzio ni kanda Ia usufi.

eng: The one who buries ivory is the one to dig it up
(For him) who is accustomed to taking giving away is a battle.
He who is used to strangle, cannot slaughter.
The process of eating is not taught to a child.
Too many captains (and) the ship rolls. Or: Too many cooks spoil the broth.
Let us see then tell; hearing is not seeing Or: Seeing is believing.
kisw: Natuone ndipo twambe, kusikia Si kuona.

eng: A rotten coconut in a heap spoils the wholesome ones. Or: A rotten apple spoils its neighbours. Or: A sickly sheep infects the whole flock.
An artful bird can be trapped in a rotten cage.
kisw: Ndege mjanja hunaswa na tundu bovu,

eng: A bird that imitates others does not get used to a place.
A brother is (as useful as) a cooking pot, and a neighbour is (as useful as) a cooking pot lid.
A bad brother is far better than no brother. Or: Blood is thicker than water.

When brothers quarrel, take a hoe and go and dig; and when they make it up, take a basket and patter the crop (i.e. never interfere with a dispute between brothers except to fly and settle it amicably).
kisw: Ndugu wakigombana, chukua jembe ukalime, wakipatana chukua kikapu ukavune..

eng: Wait a minute! wait a minute! harms the stomach
A noisy drumming does not last long.
A drum that is sounded loudly will soon split Or: A pitcher that often goes to the well, is broken at last.
Stretch hide while it is still green. Or: Strike while the iron is hot.
A good purpose is like a doctor (it heals or keeps you well) and evil purpose corrupts.
kisw: Nia njema ni tabibu, nia mbaya huharibu.

eng: Do me a favour during a rainy season and I shall do the same to you during the dry season.
kisw: Nifae na mvua nikufae na jua.

eng: I ate honey in my childhood, and its sweetness is still in my tooth.
kisw: Nimekula asali udogoni, utamu ungali gegoni.

eng: I have anointed you with kohl, do you, in return, anoint me with pepper?
The way of a liar is short (i.e. he soon comes to grief).
A regular path has no signpost. Or: A used key is always bright.
kisw: Njia ya siku zote haina alama.

eng: When a bull gets his leg broken, he is sure to go back to his yard.
A cow is not oppressed by its own hump.
Wax is not honey; 'I had them' (i.e. cattle) is not herding.
kisw: Nta Si asali; nalikuwa nazo Si uchunga.

eng: The ape does not see his own backside, he Sees his companion's.
kisw: Nyani haoni kundule, huliona la mwenziwe.

eng: Songs learnt from outside sources (foreign importations) are not used at a dance so long.
You cannot know the defects of a house you have not slept in. Or: It is the wearer who knows where the shoe pinches.
kisw: Nyumba usiyolala ndani huijui ila yake.

eng: A mud hut cannot withstand great shocks.
For a fly to die on an ulcer is not bad (after all, he got what he wanted).
kisw: Nzi kufa juu ya kidonda Si haramu.

eng: Your own bad place is far better (so far as you are concerned) than your companion's place (which will do you no good).
kisw: Pabaya pako Si pema pa mwenzako.

eng: Your own small place is not like a big place of your companion. Or: A poor thing but mine own.
kisw: Padogo pako Si pakubwa pa mwenzako.

eng: Where it slopes down is where it slopes up.
when the cat goes away, mice reign. Or: When the cat's away, the mice do play.
A cat can never he made to lie on its back.
A cat belonging to the house is not chased away.
Where there are many, nothing goes wrong. (A council of many people ensures that things are kept on the right tines.) Or: Many hands make light work.
Constant rubbing of a rope will cut a stone. Or: Constant dripping wears away a stone.
kisw: Papo kwa papo kamba hukata jiwe.

eng: Scabics are given to him who has no fingernails (i.e. who cannot scratch himself).
A good place you don't go to is a good place: if you go too often, it isn't a good place any longer. Or: Familiarity brings contempt; or, Outstay one's welcome.
kisw: Pema usijapo pema; ukipema Si pema tena.

eng: Where there are many fowls, millet is not scattered (i.e. it is not advisable to disclose a secret in the presence of a number of people).
Where there are experts there will be no lack ot learners.
Where you have an enemy, you will also surely arid a friend.
kisw: Penye mbaya wako, hapakosi mwema wako/na mwema wako hakosi.

eng: Where there are plenty of trees there are no builders.
Where there's a will there's a way.
Where there is finery, there lies the snare (Lit: birdlime).
Where there are old people, nothing goes wrong.
Where there are many (present) there is much (said).
Where there are many people, there God is
How can you be burnt by chilies which you have not eaten?
A blind person does not forget his walking stick.
A thief finds another one (who is a bigger and better thief than he is). Or: When Greek meets Greek.
Blessings are better than wealth,
When a plate is covered, its contents are hidden.
f one fish rots, they all rot. Or: A rotten apple spoils its neighbours. A sickly sheep infects the whole flock.
kisw: Samaki mmoja akioza, huoza wote. I

eng: Hold him! Hold him! and you yourself after him (i.e. you shouldn't expect others to do all the work).
A pit of (dug by) the tongue cannot be covered up by the hand (words are more dangerous). Or: The pen is mightier than the sword.
An axe with rio handle does not split firewood.
Not all that have claws are lions. Or:All that glitters is not gold.
kisw: Si kila mwenye makucha huwa simba.

eng: An ear dots not go to bed hungry (there's always plenty of gossip).
The ear does not surpass the head.
kisw: Sikio halipwani kichwa. Alt: Sikio halipiti kichwa.

eng: A dying ear does not feel the medicine.
A good day becomes evident in the morning.
The day you go naked, is the day you will meet your father/mother.in-law
kisw: Siku utakayokwenda uchi, ndiyo siku utakayokutana na mkweo.

eng: The lion which moves silently is the one that eats meat.
kisw: Simba mwenda kimya(pole) ndiye mla nyama.

eng: A thing that is firmly fixed cannot be dislodged except with much trouble.
I shall not suffer illness while doctors abound.
Patience is the key to tranquility.
Patience attracts happiness; it brings near that which is far.
kisw: Subira yavuta heri, huleta kilicho mbali.

eng: The poison for a word is a word. Or: Tit for tat.
Desire first, death afterwards, (i.e. 'No one ever thinks of the possibIlity of death when concentrating on achieving a particular end).
Slowly is indeed the way to walk, Or: He that goes slowly goes surely, or, Hasten slowly. or, Slow but sure.
A hen's kick does not hurt her chick.
The juice of an Immature coconut Is not like the real coconut juice.
The laughter of a child lights up the house.
kisw: Ucheshi wa mtoto ni anga Ia nyumba.

eng: The Iabour of childbirth is known to the mother.
Work the clay while it is still wet Or: Strike while the iron is hot
The brotherhood of coconuts is a meeting in the cook- in pot (said of people who do not cooperate until it is too late).
When you go among one-eyed people, put out your own eye. Or: Where ignorance is bliss, it is folly to be wise, or, When in Rome, do as the Romans do (?).
kisw: Ukenda kwa wenye chongo, vunja lako jicho.

eng: If you find your own house is on fire, you may be sure that your neighbour's house is burning much more fiercely.
kisw: Ukiona kwako kunaungua kwa mwenzako kunateketea.

eng: If you see something and say nothing, you will have nothing to suffer for. Or: Mind your own business, or, Hear all, see all, say nothing.
kisw: Ukiona neno, usiposema neno, hutapatikana na neno.

eng: If you see vessels afloat, remember that they have had to be built.
If you see amber, ambergis is (not far) behind, (i.e. Where there is a jealous husband, there will be jealous wife). (Sauce for the goose . . .?)
If you are offered a span, do not take a couple of yards. Or: Give him an inch and he will take an ell.
What beats you is what teaches you. Or: Spare the rod and spoil the child.
If you are astonished at Moses' deeds, you will be more astonished at Pharaoh's. Not-Moses declared himself to he a prophet, but Pharaoh declared himself to be God.
kisw: Ukistaajabu ya Mussa utaona ya Firauni.

eng: When you mention a snake, have a stick ready in your hand. Talk of the devil, and you'll hear the rustle of his wings.
If you want to eat pig, choose one which is fat. Or: As well be hanged for a sheep as a lamb. (Muslims are forbidden pork).
If you want beauty, you must (first) be injured
A well-worn coir-rope is better than a new rope made from raffia.
kisw: Ukuukuu wa kamba Si upya wa ukambaa.

eng: A tongue has no bone (i.e. it can get round anything, both literally and metaphorically).
The tongue hurts more than the teeth.
You will not necessarily get what you desire, you will get what is appointed you (by God). Or: Man proposes, God disposes.
As you tapped it (palm-wine) you will (have to) drink. Or: As you sow, so shall you reap, or, You have made your bed and now you must lie on it
Have you changed into a cuttle-fish, (that) you heap live embers on yourself?
Are you a duck (that) your mind is with your children?
Are you a Jeta, (that) you do not move?
Are you a dugong, (that) you cannot bear a wound?
You are blaming the hawk, (while) the falcon is killing the chickens.
Had you known what bees eat, you would not have tasted the honey.
When you are seized, hold on yourself.
Do not neglect the undoing (of a trap that has caught) for the setting (of others).cf. A bird in the hand is worth two in the bush.
Never give up your own old mat for a better prayer mat which you see passing.
When you play with a lion, do not put your hand in its mouth (that would be going too far!).
kisw: Usicheze na simba, ukamtia mkono kinywani.

eng: Don't quarrel with the coconut-palm climber: the coconut has been eaten by the moon.
kisw: Usigombe na mkwezi, nazi imeliwa na mwezi.

eng: Do not pretend to be a white fowl (you're only an ordinary chap).
Do not roast baobab kernels and leave those who have teeth chewing (them). Don't start quarrels among other people (bv telling tales).
kisw: Usikaange mbuyu ukawaachia wenye meno watafune.

eng: When you are eating with a blind man, do not touch his hand. (to do so will lead him to suspect that either the food is finished or you are trying to play a trick on him. In other words, with a simple person you must be very careful lest you might do something to make him suspicious of you)
Do not wake one who is sleeping; you will fall asleep yourself.
Do not put a grass turban on my head, (i.e. do not flatter me).
If you do not fill up a crack, you will have to build a wall. Or: A stitch in time saves nine
Don't travel under another's lucky star (i.e. do not rely on someone else's good fortune).
Do not forget what it is to be a sailor because of being a captain yourself.
kisw: Usisahau ubaharia kwa sababu ya unahodha.

eng: Do not compete with Kari, Kari comes from God.
kisw: Usishindane na Kari; Kari ni mja wa Mungu.

eng: Speak no ill of palm-wine tappers as long as drinking persist.
Speak no ill of midwives while childbirth still continues.
Do not cross water that is too deep for wading.
